50|$|The guerrilla {{forces had}} {{essentially}} the same desirable characteristics as the <b>mobile</b> strike <b>forces</b> with the following exceptions: the <b>mobile</b> guerrilla <b>force</b> troops were highly responsive {{to the needs of}} the Special Forces companies in each of the four corps tactical zones in that operational control rested with the Special Forces company commander for the <b>mobile</b> guerrilla <b>force</b> located in his corps tactical zone; each <b>mobile</b> guerrilla <b>force</b> unit was wholly commanded and controlled by a Special Forces A detachment (the <b>mobile</b> strike <b>forces</b> went under joint U.S.-Vietnamese Special Forces command in December 1966); and each <b>mobile</b> guerrilla <b>force</b> unit was trained to operate as an independent unit with no reinforcement or mutual support.|$|R
